Fixed code:

```java
private void handleObjectLit(NodeTraversal t, Node n) {
  for (Node child = n.getFirstChild();
      child != null;
      child = child.getNext()) {
    // Maybe STRING, GET, SET

    // We should never see a mix of numbers and strings.
    String name = child.getString();
    T type = typeSystem.getType(getScope(), n, name);

    Property prop = getProperty(name);
    if (prop != null && !prop.scheduleRenaming(child,
                                   processProperty(t, prop, type, null))) {
      // TODO(user): It doesn't look like the user can do much in this
      // case right now.
      if (propertiesToErrorFor.containsKey(name)) {
        compiler.report(JSError.make(
            t.getSourceName(), child, propertiesToErrorFor.get(name),
            Warnings.INVALIDATION, name,
            (type == null ? "null" : type.toString()), n.toString(), ""));
      }
    }
  }
}
```

But note: originally the if condition was `if (!prop.scheduleRenaming(...))`. We changed to `if (prop != null && !prop.scheduleRenaming(...))`. So if prop is null, we skip the entire if block, which means no error reporting. That might be acceptable.

Alternatively, we could keep the error reporting for null prop: if prop is null, maybe we should also check propertiesToErrorFor and report. But that would require restructuring. The minimal fix is to avoid the NPE; the error reporting for null properties may be a separate issue. Since the original code would have crashed, any behavior after that is an improvement. So I'll go with this minimal fix.

